The helper functions in acceptance/lib/puppet/acceptance/rpm_util.rb do not verify that the packages {{createrepo}} and {{rpmbuild}} are present on the system under test prior to invoking them.

This is causing the following acceptance test to fail:

{{acceptance/tests/resource/package.common_package_name_in_different_providers.rb}}

When running something that fails and using the {{--trace}} flag to get a stack trace, no stack trace appears. This works on 3.7.5, but not on 3.x.

Expected:
{code}
puppet apply -e '1 < blue' --parser future --trace
{code}

to produce a stack trace, but no stack trace is produced.

The {{TypeCalculator.generalize}} strips all information about type and represented value (or values) when applied to a {{String}}. This behavior becomes problematic when generalizing a {{Struct}} type since it means that all information about the keys in that struct is lost and a printout of a generalized Struct becomes nonsensical. The struct:
{code}
Struct[{name => String[1], version => String[1]}]
{code}
becomes:
{code}
Struct[{'' => String, '' => String}]
{code}

When a variable containing a hash has a name prefixed with an underscore:
{noformat}
$_foo = {
  'a' => 'b',
}
notify { "${_foo['a']}": }
{noformat}

and run `puppet apply --parser=future` you get the following error:
{noformat}
Error: Evaluation Error: The value 'a' cannot be converted to Numeric. on node uagent2.corp.puppetlabs.net
Error: Evaluation Error: The value 'a' cannot be converted to Numeric. on node uagent2.corp.puppetlabs.net
{noformat}

That looks like it might be assuming that the hash is an array?

The following applies without error:
{noformat}
$foo = {
  'a' => 'b',
}
notify { "${foo['a']}": }
{noformat}

This fails with the future parser on puppet 3.7.5, and also fails against master (at 7ba7ae8f3b221896a3b77beb6778b7a895671c7d)

Per [~henrik.lindberg] in email, this is supposed to work... but it totally doesn't.

{code}
notify {'first':}

$myattrs = {"message" => "from a reference attribute block"}

Notify[first] { *=> $myattrs }
# Error: Could not parse for environment production: The operator '* =>' in an Object is not supported. at /Users/nick/Documents/splat_reference.pp:5:17 on node magpie.lan

