According to https://docs.puppetlabs.com/puppet/latest/reference/future_lang_conditional.html#behavior-2 the future parser should always evaluate the default case last; however, that does not seem to be happening.  The following code, executed on a VM always returns the default case.

{code:puppet}
[root@master ~]# facter is_virtual
true
[root@master ~]# cat foo.pp
case $is_virtual {
  default: { notify { "default case": } }
  true: { notify { "nondefault case": } }
}
[root@master ~]# puppet apply foo.pp
Notice: Compiled catalog for master.inf.puppetlabs.demo in environment production in 0.51 seconds
Notice: default case
Notice: /Stage[main]/Main/Notify[default case]/message: defined 'message' as 'default case'
Notice: Finished catalog run in 0.28 seconds
{code}

Type TypeCalculator.infer is used when type constrained resource parameters are validated which means that important information is lost when an error message is printed. The following expression:
{code}
define foo(Struct[{b => Integer, d=>String}] $a) { notice $a }
foo{ bar: a => {b => 5, c => 'stuff'}}
{code}
currently results in the following error message:
{code}
Error: Expected parameter 'a' of 'Foo[bar]' to have type Struct[{'b'=>Integer, 'd'=>String}], got Hash[String, Scalar]
{code}
the correct output (when using `infer_set` instead of `infer`) should be:
{code}
Error: Expected parameter 'a' of 'Foo[bar]' to have type Struct[{'b'=>Integer, 'd'=>String}], got Struct[{'b'=>Integer, 'c'=>String}]
{code}

Unicode includes a bunch of 5+ hex digit characters now; most notably emoji, but I think there might be some real human language characters in there too.

Puppet's \u escape sequences don't accommodate these. The 5-digit versions get truncated, and the alternate 2x4-digit forms result in an error. 

{code}
notice("5 digit unicode \u1f452 hat") # prints: 5 digit unicode á½…2 hat
# notice("double 4 digit unicode \uD83D\uDC52 hat") # Results in Error: Could not parse for environment production: invalid byte sequence in UTF-8 on node magpie.lan
notice("literal ðŸ‘’ hat") # works fine
{code}

h2. Update
The implementation allows using the escape 
{code}
\u{nnnn}
{code}
 where n is 1 or more hex digits.
{code:puppet}
notice("5 digit unicode \u{1f452} hat")
{code}

h2. QA Risk Analysis
| Probability | Medium (anyone using 5+ byte unicode characters)|
| Impact | Medium (broken Unicode support breaks puppet) |
| Risk Level | Medium |
| Test Level | Spec |

I expected the following to be equivalent:

Function call sytnax:
{code}
with(*[1, 2, 3]) |$x, $y, $z| {
    notice $x, $y, $z
}
{code}

Method call syntax:
{code}
(*[1, 2, 3]).with |$x, $y, $z| {
    notice $x, $y, $z
}
{code}

The function call outputs:
{code}
Notice: Scope(Class[main]): 1 2 3
{code}

The method call outputs an error:
{code}
Error: Evaluation Error: Parameter $y is required but no value was given at...
{code}

In the latter, $x is the array without being unfolded.

