The following sort of code no longer works after a recent change to puppet:

{code}
define producer($foo) { }
Producer produces Capres {
  foo => $foo,
}

define consumer($foo) { }
Consumer consumes Capres {
  foo => $foo,
}

application myapp() {
  producer { something:
    foo => "some value",
    export => Capres[name],
  }

  consumer { something:
    consume => Capres[name],
  }
}
{code}

The gist of this application is that some parameter {{$foo}} is set on a producer, which attempts to convey that value to a consumer via a capability resource. However, when evaluating an instance of the application during environment catalog compilation, the consumer's parameters are validated and it fails because there is no value supplied for the {{$foo}} parameter.

In reality, this situation is perfectly acceptable, as no parameters are meant to be set in the environment catalog. We only want to know the type and title of the resources, along with the capabilities that they exchange. On the agent node, the parameters will be populated by the capability resources that are consumed. At environment compilation time, the capabilities haven't been produced and so that doesn't work.

It seems the solution to this problem is to avoid setting and/or validating resource params during environment catalog compilation, since all we care about are the identities of the resources involved. We can't actually set the parameters at this time, since their defaults/values may depend on node facts that aren't available during environment catalog compilation.

This seems likely to have been introduced by https://github.com/puppetlabs/puppet/commit/fcf939ebc287eb6ceba7126199c26afc673c44a4.

