The {{ip}}, {{dataset}} and {{inherit}} properties of the Zone type each have [insync methods|https://github.com/puppetlabs/puppet/blob/3.6.2/lib/puppet/type/zone.rb#L252-L253] that respond with {{true}} when passed a {{nil}} property value. When a zone resource is first created, the property hash looks like:

{code}
{
  ensure => :absent
}
{code}

This means that every property value aside from {{ensure}} is {{nil}} which causes ip, dataset and inherit to be skipped during zone creation. After creation, {{:absent}} is used in the hash instead of {{nil}}.

However, in the case of {{inherit}}, the inherited directories of a Solaris 10 zone cannot be changed after creation:

{noformat}
echo "add inherit-pkg-dir
set dir=/opt/puppet
end
commit" | /usr/sbin/zonecfg -z test -f -

On line 1:
Zone test already installed; add inherit-pkg-dir not allowed.
On line 2:
Cannot set a resource-specific property from the global scope.
On line 3:
The end command only makes sense in the resource scope.
{noformat}

To quote the official [Solaris 10 documentation|http://docs.oracle.com/cd/E19044-01/sol.containers/817-1592/z.conf.start-29/index.html]:

{quote}
These resources cannot be modified or removed after the zone has been installed using zoneadm.
{quote}

So, eventual consistency does no good for the {{inherit}} property.

The systemd service provider is using the following command to determine its enabled state

{code:sh}
systemctl show autofs --property LoadState --property UnitFileState
{code}

Normally this returns
{code}
# systemctl show autofs --property LoadState --property UnitFileState
LoadState=loaded
UnitFileState=enabled
{code}

In a chroot
{code}
# systemctl show autofs --property LoadState --property UnitFileState
Running in a chroot, ignoring request.
{code}

Therefore, the provider always enables the autofs service.

This can be overcome by using 'systemctl is-enabled'

In a chroot
{code}
# systemctl is-enabled autofs
enabled
{code}

